AWS now spans 70 Availability Zones within 22 geographic regions around the world

In Default VPC, there is no concept of private subnets.
In non Default VPC,there is no concept of public IPs, we have to depend upon elastic IPs

NACL is a firewall that allows /denies the traffic wrt subnet. It will process the rules from top to bottom and allows/denies the 
traffic as per the rule configured.

Configure AWS CLI:

C:\Users\Sachin Arora>aws configure
AWS Access Key ID [****************7ANQ]: AKIAI4TDR5WATOZLN7CQ
AWS Secret Access Key [****************KkQs]: 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
Default region name [ap-south-1]:
Default output format [json]:


aws ec2 create-security-group --group-name "My CLI Group" --description --"My AWS CLI Group"
aws ec2 describe-security-groups --group-name "My CLI Group"
aws ec2 authorize-security-group-ingress --group-name "My CLI Group" --protocol tcp --port 22 --cidr 0.0.0.0/0 
aws ec2 create-key-pair --key-name cli-kps --query "KeyMaterial" --output text > cli-kps.pem
aws ec2 run-instances --count 1 --image-id ami-04b2519c83e2a7ea5 --security-groups "My CLI Group" --key-name cli-kps 
--instance-type t2.micro
aws ec2 describe-instances --instance-id xyz 



VPC Peering:
2 diff VPCs should be in the same region
2 diff VPCs should not have ovelapping CIDR block ranges
Transative peering connections are not allowed
